{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15045"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.25,0.04,0.21,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7733"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67567"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7733"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7682"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18889"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67567"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man develops acute tubular necrosis following severe muscle injury (rhabdomyolysis). A kidney biopsy specimen is examined under light microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of renal casts is most likely to be visible on microscopic examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["White cell casts","Red cell casts","Waxy casts","Hyaline casts","Pigmented granular casts"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn rhabdomyolysis-induced acute tubular necrosis, \u003Cstrong\u003Epigmented granular casts\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristically seen due to myoglobin precipitation within the renal tubules. These casts appear reddish-brown under microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other types of casts indicate different pathological processes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite cell casts\u003C/strong\u003E indicate inflammation or infection within the kidney, such as in pyelonephritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed cell casts\u003C/strong\u003E are diagnostic of glomerular bleeding, as seen in glomerulonephritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaxy casts\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in chronic kidney disease and represent degenerated cellular casts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E are composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein and are commonly seen in normal urine or with mild proteinuria\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of pigmented granular casts, along with elevated serum creatine kinase and dark urine, helps confirm the diagnosis of rhabdomyolysis-induced acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Myoglobin casts appear reddish-brown and are characteristic of acute tubular necrosis caused by rhabdomyolysis","Different types of urinary casts indicate specific kidney pathologies - hyaline (normal/mild disease), waxy (chronic disease), cellular (acute inflammation/injury)","The presence of red cell casts specifically indicates glomerular bleeding"],"references":["Dvanajscak Z, Cossey LN, Larsen CP. A practical approach to the pathology of renal intratubular casts. Semin Diagn Pathol. 2020 May;37(3):127-134. doi: 10.1053/j.semdp.2020.02.001. Epub 2020 Feb 14. PMID: 32147230","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:13:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:14:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7733"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67567"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio